binding.p: Rebound in the 19th century and in 1958 by Sven Wiklander (see notes on ). The wooden boards, of uncertain date, are covered with modern brown goatskin; 2 new clasps.
binding.decoNote: On the front cover a badly damaged double framed miniature (now flattened out but formerly wrinkled, probably as a result of the fire in 1697). The miniature was covered by plexiglass in 1958 but was originally protected by a transparent horn plate fastened by strips of silver or horn, small pieces of which are now attached to the inner face of the box. The miniature shows St. Bartholomew, holding a book in his right hand. The words "Sanctus Bartholomeus" are inscribed on the top of the frame. Outer fields: on the top the busts of the apostles James and Thomas with name scrolls, on the bottom the busts of Philip the Apostle with a name scroll and unidentified apostle (scroll probably lost); along the sides quatrefoils in a double row of lozenges.

history.origin:
Germany , 13th century
The litany of saints mentions e.g. St. Willehad, bishop of Bremen . However, his feast day (8 November) is not noted in the Calendar. Among saints mentioned in the Calendar are St Godehard of Hildesheim 5 May, St Germanus of Auxerre 31 July; St. Willibrord 7 November.
The Calendar could suggest an origin in Lower Saxony, with mentions of e.g. St Suitbert (8 May), Sts Cantius, Cantianus and Cantanilla (31 May), Margaret the Virgin (13 July), cf. Kroos (1964)
.
Swarzenski suggests a Franconian origin due to the decoration and binding but the liturgical evidence, such as the calendar, the series of the responsories and the readings of the Office of the Dead suggest otherwise.
history.provenance: The addition "S. Olaui" on , presumably a later addition, could suggest a Scandinavian ownership in the Middle Ages.

Antikvitetsarkivet. Listed in the inventory U 90:2 (f. 9v no 135) as 'Liber precum latine’; U 90:4, p. 48, no 135; U 91:2 'Andelige böcker på pergament in quarto': G 135 /30; U 91:5, N. iv. and above it xvi.

Berch’s catalogue has A 30 (current signum). An older label (A 30) has been cut out and pasted on the paper endleaf . Berch notes that the cover was decorated in the past with pictures covered by a thin horn plate (today kept at the inside of the box). Such a practise is mentioned by Swarzenski, p. 109, footnote 3.
history.acquisition: From Antikvitetsarkivet to the National Library.

Prayers added by a later hand, possibly the same hand as . Incipit: "Sancta Maria virgo virginum."

decoDesc.p: The manuscript is decorated throughout. The embellishments around some of the initials may have been added by a later hand, according to Art historian Eva Lindqvist Sandgren.
